CARUCATE. A carucate of land;
Britt. c. 84.

plow-land.

CATER COUSIN. (From Fr. Quatre-
Cousin.) A cousin in the fourth degree;
hence any distant or remote relative.

CHANCERY. Equity; equitable jurisdiction; a court of equity; the system of jurisprudence administered in courts of equity.
Kenyon vy. Kenyon, 3 Utah, 431, 24 Pac. 829;
Sullivan v. Thomas, 3 Rich. (S. C.) 531. Nee

CIBARIA. Lat.
victuals. Dig. 34, L


In the civil law. Food;

CLERIGOS. In Spanish law. Clergy;
men chosen for the service of God. White,
New Recop. b. 1, tit. 5, ch. 4

COMITISSA.
Countess;

In old English law. A countess; an earl's wife.

COMMAND. An order, imperative direction, or behest. State 'v. Mann, 2 N. C. 4;
Barney v. Hayes, 11 Mont. 571, 29 Pac. 282,
28 Am. St. Rep. 490.

COMPOUND, v. To compromise; to effect a composition with a creditor; to obtain discharge from a debt by the payment
of a smaller sum. Bank v. Malheur County, 30 Or. 420, 45 Pac. 781, 35 L. R. A. 141;
Haskins v. Newcomb, 2 Johns. (N. Y.) 405;
Pennell v. Rhodes, 9 Q. B. 114.

CONJURATOR. In old English law.
One who swears or is sworn with others;
one bound by oath with others; a compurgator; a conspirator.

CONTRATENEUR.
to withhold. Whishaw.


To hold against;

CONTROVERT. To dispute; to deny;
to oppose or contest; to take issue on. Buggy Co. v. Patt, 73 Iowa, 485, 35 N. W. 587;
Swenson v. Kleinschmidt, 10 Mont. 473, 26
Pac. 198.

CONVENTIONE. The name of a writ
for the breach of any covenant in writing,
whether real or personal. Reg. Orig. 115;
Fitzh. Nat. Brev. 145.

COOPERIUM. In forest law. A covert;
a thicket (dumetum) or shelter for wild
beasts in a forest. Spelman.

CROITEIR. A crofter;
croft.

one holding a

CUT. A wound made with a sharp instrument. State v. Patza, 3 La. Ann. 512;
State v. Cody, 18 Or. 506, 23 Pac. 891; State
v. Mairs, 1 N. J. Law, 453.
